extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 169 x 129 mm., on sheet 261x 181 mm
Additional Notes: Printed in color for the frist time and with the prefaces by Philip Hofer and John Winterich

title: Book VI. L. 864-865
description:
The Rout of the Rebel Angels: Headlong themselves they threw
Down from the verge of Heaven; eternal wrath
Burnt after them to the bottomless pit.
image_alt_text: Angel shots arrow at falling angels
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
Additional Notes: All images in this book are in pen and watercolor over pencil and were executed in 1808.  This edition was set in 16-point 'Monotype' Bembo, 2 points leaded, with Centaur display type by Gloucester Typesetting Services, Stonehouse, Glos. Printed by Cambridge University Press on Caxton Wove paper, with the illustrations on Phoenix Motion Xenon, and bound by then in Nigerian goatskin leather with Moire silk sides. Preface by Peter Ackroyd, an intorduction by John Wain.

title: Book I. L. 314-334
description:
Satan Arousing the Rebel Angels - He call'd so loud, that all the hollow deep
Of Hell resounded: 'Princes, Potentates
Warriors, the flower of Heaven, once yours, now lost, 
If such astonishment as this can seize   Eternal Spirits: or have ye chosen this place   After the toil of battle to repose  Your wearied virtue, for the ease you find   To slumber here, as in the valves of Heaven?
image_alt_text: Satan stands among fallen angels
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
column23: The Victoria and Albert Museum, London

title: Book II. L. 648-676
description:
Satan, Sin and Death: Satan Comes to the Gates of Hell - Yet unconsumed. Before the Gates there sat
On either side a formidable Shape.
The one seem'd woman to the waist, and fair,
But ended foul in many a scaly fold
Voluminous and vast, a serpent arm'd
With mortal sting.
image_alt_text: Satan at the gates of Hell with Death and Sin personified
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 291 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
column23: The Huntington Library, Arts Collections and Botanical Gardens, San Marino, California

title: Book III. L. 227-230
description:
Christ offers to Redeem Man - 'Father, thy word is pass'd, Man shall find grace;
And shall grace not find means, that finds her way,
The speediest of thy winged messengers,
To visit all thy creatures
image_alt_text: God-like figure holds Christ-like figure
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 305 x 240 mm
rightsstatement: 2002 The Museum of Fine Arts, Boston

title: Book IV. L. 797-800
description:
Adam and Eve Sleeping - So saying, on he led his radiant files,
Dazzling the moon; these to the bower direct
In search of whom they sough. Him there they found
Squat like a toad, close at the ear of Eve,
image_alt_text: Two angels watch Adam and Eve
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
rightsstatement: 2003 The Museum of Fine Arts, Boston

title: Book V. L. 443-446
description:
Raphael warns Adam and Eve - Mean while at Table Eve
Minister'd naked, and their flowing cups
With pleasant liquors crown'd. O innocence 
Deserving Paradise!
image_alt_text: Angel talks with Adam and Eve
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 301 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
rightsstatement: 2004 The Museum of Fine Arts, Boston

title: Book VIII. L. 471-472
description:
The Creation of Eve - So saying, her rash hand in evil hour 
Forth reaching to the Fruit, she pluck'd, she eat
image_alt_text: God creates Eve
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 304 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm

title: Book IX. L. 780-781
description:
The Temptation and Fall of Eve - So saying, her rash hand in evil hour 
Forth reaching to the Fruit, she pluck'd, she eat
image_alt_text: Snake feeds Eve fruit
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm

title: Book X. L. 209-212
subjectcontents: Adam; Eve; God; Sin; Death; Serpent; Eden
description:
The Judgment of Adam and Eve - So judged he Man, both Judge and Saviour sent,
And the instant stroke of death, denounced that day,
Removed far off; then pittying how they stood
Before him naked to the aire
image_alt_text: Adam and Eve talking with God
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
column23: *65M-123. The Houghton Library, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts

title: Book XII. L. 411-431
subjectcontents: Michael; Adam; Eve; Christ; Crucifixion; Sin; Death; Serpent; Cross
description:
Michael Foretells the Crucifixion - For this he shall live hated, be blasphemed,
Seized on by force, judged, and to death condemned,
A shameful and accurst, nail'd to the Cross
By his own Nation, slaine for bringing Life;
But to the Cross he nailes thy Enemies
image_alt_text: Angel shows Adam the cruicifixion
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
rightsstatement: 2002 The Museum of Fine Arts, Boston

title: Book XII. L. 632-644
subjectcontents: Michael; Adam; Eve; God; Angels; Serpent
description:
The Expulsion of Adam and Eve from the Garden of Eden - In either hand the hastening angel caught
Our lingering parents, and to the eastern gate
Led them direct, and down the cliff as fast To the subjected plain; then dissapear'd.
image_alt_text: Angel leads Adam and Eve out of garden
extent: 1 print: engraving ; image 316 x 240 mm., on sheet 316 x 240 mm
rightsstatement: 2002 The Museum of Fine Arts, Boston
